=== EXAMPLE: scdoc_Guides_Level_Compensation_ex6 ===

DESCRIPTION: A bright clean sound, with sine_like oscillator character around 50 Hz, featuring moderate attack and dynamic envelope, with chaotic spectral movement, and filtered with steep_rolloff character.

CATEGORIES:
  attack_time: moderate
  brightness: bright
  crest_factor_db: dynamic
  envelope_flatness: flat
  harmonic_to_noise_ratio: clean
  spectral_complexity_mean: moderate
  spectral_flux_normalized: chaotic
  spectral_slope: steep_rolloff
  temporal_centroid: balanced

SYNTHESIS CONCEPTS (key values):
[oscillator]
  fundamental_freq: 50.0000
  harmonic_decay_rate: -3.6172
  harmonic_regularity: 0.9579
  pitch_clarity: 53.8937
  inharmonicity: 0.0175
  type: sine_like
[filter]
  spectral_slope: -18.4087
  resonance_freq: 0.0000

SUPERCOLLIDER CODE:
// Title: Level Compensation when Mixing and Panning Example 6
// Author: SC Documentation
// URL: http://doc.sccode.org/Guides/Level_Compensation.html
// Tags: Level_Compensation, Guides
// ---
// --- Example 6 ---
s.meter; s.play;

// levelComp defaults to true, which is equal power -
// this is kept this way for backwards compatibility.
{ Splay.ar(Saw.ar([20, 30, 50]), 1, levelComp: true) }.play;
// levelComp can be turned off to set level otherwise:
{ Splay.ar(Saw.ar([20, 30, 50]), level: 0.6, levelComp: false) }.play;

// levelComp can be a number between 0.0 -> no comp,
// and 1.0 -> equal amplitude comp, with 0.5 being equal power,
// which allows fine/tuning by hand via the exponent:
{ Splay.ar(Saw.ar([100, 150, 250]), levelComp: 0.5) }.play;

// When setting spread low, levels and peaks will go up;
// the worst case is panning all inputs to a single channel:
{ Splay.ar(Saw.ar([100, 150, 250]), spread: 0, center: 1, levelComp: 0.5) }.play;
